Using our first decision tree algorithm from OneR package

OneR algorithm takes into account only ONE most feature for RULE generation

iris_1R <- OneR(Species ~ ., data = df)
iris_1R
## 
## Call:
## OneR.formula(formula = Species ~ ., data = df)
## 
## Rules:
## If Petal.Width = (0.0976,0.58] then Species = setosa
## If Petal.Width = (0.58,1.06]   then Species = versicolor
## If Petal.Width = (1.06,1.54]   then Species = versicolor
## If Petal.Width = (1.54,2.02]   then Species = virginica
## If Petal.Width = (2.02,2.5]    then Species = virginica
## 
## Accuracy:
## 141 of 150 instances classified correctly (94%)

We see the OneR algorithm has an accuracy of 94%

Comparing our predicted values with Actual values with help of confusion matrix and exploring our model with graph

iris_1R_pred <- predict(iris_1R, df)
table(actual = df$Species, predicted = iris_1R_pred)
##             predicted
## actual       setosa versicolor virginica
##   setosa         49          1         0
##   versicolor      0         45         5
##   virginica       0          3        47
plot(iris_1R)

Improving performance with more robust models

We now load our RWeka package and use the JRip algorithm

library(RWeka)
## 
## Attaching package: 'RWeka'
## The following object is masked from 'package:OneR':
## 
##     OneR
iris_classifier <- JRip(Species ~ ., data = df)
iris_classifier
## JRIP rules:
## ===========
## 
## (Petal.Length <= 1.9) => Species=setosa (50.0/0.0)
## (Petal.Width <= 1.7) and (Petal.Length <= 4.9) => Species=versicolor (48.0/1.0)
##  => Species=virginica (52.0/3.0)
## 
## Number of Rules : 3
summary(iris_classifier)
## 
## === Summary ===
##

CostSensitive Classifier

m2 <- CostSensitiveClassifier(Species ~ ., data = df, 
control = Weka_control(`cost-matrix` = matrix(c(0,10, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 10, 0), 
ncol = 3), 
W = "weka.classifiers.trees.J48", 
M = TRUE))

m2

The task is complete but explored more libraries for better results and easier implementation

The rpart library provides the easiest way to make a decision tree.

tree <- rpart(Species ~ ., data = df, cp=.02)
summary(tree)
